Machine Credit Protocol (MCP)
Trust Infrastructure for Agenet


1. Motivation

As autonomous AI agents begin collaborating across digital networks, a fundamental challenge emerges:

How can machines evaluate the trustworthiness of other machines?

Traditional internet infrastructure solves identity and encryption problems through protocols such as PKI and TLS.

However, identity alone does not establish trust.

In a network of autonomous agents, trust must emerge from behavior, reputation, and collaborative history.

Machine Credit Protocol (MCP) proposes a framework for establishing trust among autonomous agents in the Agenet.

2. Core Idea

Machine Credit Protocol enables agents to evaluate one another through three primary signals:

Identity
Behavior
Peer Evaluation

Together these signals form a Machine Credit Profile for each agent.

3. MCP Architecture

The protocol can be conceptualized as four layers.

Machine Credit Protocol
│
├── Agent Identity Layer
│
├── Behavior Ledger Layer
│
├── Peer Evaluation Layer
│
└── Reputation Graph Layer

Each layer contributes to the credit profile of an agent.

4. Agent Identity Layer

Every autonomous agent requires a persistent identity within the network.

Possible mechanisms include:

cryptographic identities

decentralized identifiers (DID)

agent wallets

Identity allows agents to establish continuity across interactions.

Without identity, reputation cannot accumulate.

5. Behavior Ledger Layer

All interactions between agents can produce verifiable records.

These may include:

task completion records

performance metrics

transaction logs

collaboration outcomes

This layer functions as a behavior ledger describing what an agent has done within the network.

Unlike traditional financial ledgers, the behavior ledger records actions rather than assets.

6. Peer Evaluation Layer

After interactions occur, participating agents may provide feedback on the collaboration.

Possible evaluation signals include:

task quality

reliability

response time

cooperation quality

These evaluations allow agents to share experience about other agents.

7. Reputation Graph Layer

As evaluations accumulate, a network structure emerges.

Agent A trusts Agent B
Agent B collaborates with Agent C
Agent C recommends Agent D

These relationships form a global reputation graph.

In this graph:

nodes represent agents

edges represent trust relationships

Reputation scores can be derived from the structure of this graph.

8. Machine Credit Profile

Each agent in the network may possess a Machine Credit Profile.

This profile may contain multiple dimensions:

Reliability
Performance
Collaboration
Trust Score

Instead of a single rating, credit becomes a multi-dimensional profile reflecting the agent’s historical behavior.

9. Role of MCP in Agenet

Machine Credit Protocol acts as the trust infrastructure of Agenet.

Without a trust layer, large-scale collaboration among autonomous agents becomes unstable.

MCP enables agents to:

discover reliable collaborators

allocate tasks efficiently

avoid malicious actors

form long-term cooperation networks

10. Relationship to Existing Systems

MCP complements existing infrastructure rather than replacing it.

Examples:

PKI → identity verification
Blockchains → transaction records
MCP → behavioral trust layer

Together these layers may support the emergence of collaborative intelligence networks.

11. Open Questions

Several research challenges remain open:

how to prevent reputation manipulation

how to weight peer evaluations

how to maintain privacy while ensuring transparency

how to scale reputation graphs across millions of agents

These questions form part of the broader Agenet research agenda.

12. Conclusion

Machine Credit Protocol proposes a framework for enabling trust among autonomous agents.

As networks of AI agents expand, behavioral reputation systems may become essential infrastructure.

If the internet connected information, and social networks connected people, then collaborative intelligence networks will require a trust layer.

Machine Credit Protocol is one possible foundation for that layer.
